label.value: abnormal gamma-tubulin complex assembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which gamma-tubulin complex assembly is abnormal.

label.value: abnormal negative regulation of DNA replication initiation during mitotic G2 phase resulting in complete rereplication

value.value: A regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which negative regulation of the initiation of DNA-dependent DNA replication is abnormal, with replication reinitiating during G2 phase of the mitotic cell cycle and resulting in one or more rounds of rereplication of the entire genome.

label.value: replication origin firing during mitotic G2 phase

value.value: A regulation phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which DNA replication is initiated at one or more origins during G2 phase of the mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: increased protein localization to chromatin during mitotic G2 phase

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin is increased during G2 phase of the mitotic cell cycle.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased rate of DNA replication during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the rate, or speed, of DNA replication is increased.

label.value: normal transcriptional response to pheromone

value.value: A conjugation phenotype in which regulation of transcription in response to mating pheromone is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal S-phase DNA damage checkpoint during cellular response to hydroxyurea

value.value: A cell cycle checkpoint phenotype in which the S-phase DNA damage checkpoint (also known as the intra-S phase DNA damage checkpoint) is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) when the cell is exposed to hydroxyurea. The S phase DNA damage checkpoint slows progression through S phase in response to DNA damage.

label.value: normal linear element morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of all or part of the linear element is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: inviable after spore germination, without cell division, elongated cell

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce an inviable cell that does not divide and is elongated.

label.value: decreased chromatin silencing at subtelomere

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which chromatin silencing at subtelomeric regions is decreased.

definition.value: Chromatin silencing phenotypes may reflect the assembly or maintenance of heterochromatin. See the GO cellular component term 'heterochromatin' (GO:0000792), and the biological process term 'heterochromatin organization' (GO:0070828).

label.value: decreased distance travelled by the spindle pole body during horsetail movement

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the total distance travelled by the SPB during horsetail movement is decreased. Horsetail movement is the oscillatory movement of the nucleus that takes place during meiotic prophase I. PMID:24954111

label.value: normal protein level during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during the meiotic cell cycle is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: abnormal spindle pole body morphology

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the spindle pole body is abnormal.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal spindle pole body organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal spindle pole body structure.

label.value: abnormal spindle pole body morphology during meiosis II

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which the size, shape, or structure of the spindle pole body is abnormal during the second meiotic nuclear division.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal spindle pole body organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal spindle pole body structure.

label.value: spindle pole bodies present in increased numbers during meiosis

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype in which cells contain more spindle pole bodies (SPBs) than normal during one or both meiotic nuclear divisions. In this phenotype, extra SPBs typically contain normal components but seldom attach to spindle microtubules.

label.value: increased duration of meiotic prophase I

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the duration of prophase of the first meiotic nuclear division is longer than normal.

label.value: long interphase microtubules

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells form cytoplasmic microtubules that are longer than normal during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle.

label.value: long astral microtubules

value.value: A physical cellular phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells form astral microtubules that are longer than normal.

label.value: abolished microtubule attachment to spindle pole body

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the spindle pole body is not attached to any interphase cytoplasmic microtubules; as a result, the microtubules are not connected to the nucleus. Normally, the spindle pole body is attached to at least one cytoplasmic microtubule bundle.

definition.value: This phenotype may result from either absence of the microtubule bundle that would normally attach to the SPB, or from a problem with the SPB-microtubule attachment process.

label.value: abnormal microtubule polymerization during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which microtubule polymerization, i.e. the addition of tubulin dimers to the plus end of a microtubule, is abnormal.

label.value: increased rate of mitotic interphase microtubule polymerization

value.value: A microtubule cytoskeleton organization phenotype observed during interphase of the mitotic cell cycle in which cytoplasmic microtubule polymerization, i.e. the addition of tubulin dimers to the plus end of a cytoplasmic microtubule, occurs at a higher rate, or speed, than normal.

label.value: abolished cytoplasmic microtubule depolymerization at plus end at cell tip

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cytoplasmic microtubule depolymerization, i.e. the removal of tubulin dimers from a cytoplasmic microtubule, does not occur at the plus end of the microtubule at the cell tip. Normally, rapid depolymerization takes place when the growing plus end of the microtubule reaches the cell tip.

label.value: astral microtubules absent from cell

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the cell does not contain detectable astral microtubules.

label.value: cytoplasmic microtubules nucleated from eMTOC absent from cell

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the cell does not contain detectable cytoplasmic microtubules nucleated from the equatorial microtubule organizing center (eMTOC).

label.value: abnormal spindle disassembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which spindle disassembly is abnormal. Spindle disassembly is the controlled breakdown of the spindle.

label.value: abnormal mitotic spindle disassembly

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which disassembly of the mitotic spindle is abnormal.

label.value: abolished mitotic spindle disassembly

value.value: A cell phenotype in which mitotic spindle disassembly does not occur.

definition.value: When the mitotic spindle is not disassembled, it can become bent or S-shaped, and remains present in the cell after anaphase.

label.value: abolished astral microtubule anchoring at mitotic spindle pole body

value.value: A cell phenotype in which astral microtubule anchoring at the mitotic spindle pole body does not occur.

label.value: abolished eMTOC assembly

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which equatorial microtubule organizing center (eMTOC) assembly does not occur. eMTOC assembly is the aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form an equatorial microtubule organizing center.

label.value: abnormal post-anaphase microtubule array organization

value.value: A microtubule cytoskeleton organization phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which post-anaphase microtubule array organization is abnormal. Post-anaphase microtubule array organization is a cellular process that results in the assembly, arrangement of constituent parts, or disassembly of the post-anaphase microtubule array.

definition.value: Note that an abnormal post-anaphase microtubule array organization process may, but does not necessarily, result in abnormal post-anaphase microtubule array structure.

label.value: inviable curved elongated mononucleate vegetative cell

value.value: A cell morphology phenotype in which a vegetatively growing cell is inviable, is elongated, is curved along the long axis, and contains one nucleus. In a curved cell, the long axis follows a smooth bend rather than a straight line.

label.value: inviable after spore germination, multiple cell divisions, chromosome fragmentation upon segregation

value.value: A phenotype in which a spore germinates to produce a cell that undergoes two or more rounds of cell division during which chromosomes are broken during mitotic chromosome segregation, and then dies.

label.value: delayed onset of premeiotic DNA replication

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which premeiotic DNA replication begins later than normal.

label.value: normal mitotic DNA replication

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which mitotic DNA replication is normal.

label.value: decreased RNA level during meiotic cell cycle

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of RNA measured in a cell is lower than normal during the meiotic cell cycle. Total RNA or a specific RNA may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal transcription or abnormal regulation of transcription, but note that changes in RNA levels may result from changes in RNA stability as well as changes in transcription. We recommend noting which RNA(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein level during meiotic anaphase I

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during anaphase of the first meiotic nuclear division is lower than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein level during meiosis II

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during the second meiotic nuclear division is lower than normal. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: Consider annotating to a term describing abnormal translation or abnormal regulation of translation, but note that changes in protein levels may result from changes in protein stability or degradation as well as changes in protein synthesis. We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased protein kinase activity during meiosis II

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a protein kinase activity is decreased during the second meiotic nuclear division.

label.value: normal protein level during meiosis

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of protein measured in a cell during one or both meiotic nuclear divisions is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: increased protein localization to mitotic spindle

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to the mitotic spindle is increased.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal DNA-directed DNA polymerase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate and other catalytic properties of a DNA-directed DNA polymerase activity are normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abnormal cellular physical quality phenotype

value.value: A phenotype in which any physical object quality, such as morphology, number, location, etc., of a cell or a cellular component is abnormal.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

label.value: abnormal cellular physical quality phenotype during vegetative growth

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which any physical object quality, such as morphology, number, location, etc., of a cell or a cellular component is abnormal.

definition.value: This is a high-level term whose primary purpose is to organize terms beneath it in the ontology, and we expect that it will not be used for direct annotations. Please consider using a more specific term to annotate each phenotype.

label.value: abnormal CAAX-protein geranylgeranyltransferase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of CAAX-protein geranylgeranyltransferase activity is abnormal.

label.value: decreased CAAX-protein geranylgeranyltransferase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of CAAX-protein geranylgeranyltransferase activity is decreased.

label.value: normal protein farnesyltransferase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a protein farnesyltransferase activity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: normal Rab geranylgeranyltransferase activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of Rab geranylgeranyltransferase activity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abnormal bis(5'-nucleosyl)-tetraphosphatase (asymmetrical) activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of bis(5'-nucleosyl)-tetraphosphatase (asymmetrical) activity is abnormal.

label.value: increased bis(5'-nucleosyl)-tetraphosphatase (asymmetrical) activity

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of bis(5'-nucleosyl)-tetraphosphatase (asymmetrical) activity is increased.

label.value: normal duration of mitotic anaphase

value.value: A cell cycle phenotype in which the duration of anaphase of mitosis normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
